title: GoPro mount for Anet A8 with frame brace

description.text:
I was looking for a good mount for my Gopro to do time lapse videos but the one I found was for the Anet without the upgraded Frame Brace that most of us use. So I re-did the whole thing from scratch in Fusion 360 using the same design as the Gopro Mount by Stepher. I changed all the dimensions of the design and use a different holder for the Gopro. Still credits to him for coming up with the original idea....

I printed this using ABS because I ran out of orange PLA but forgot to turn off the fan, so its a little bend in some areas in the legs. The design is a perfect fit in my Anet A8 with the Frame Brace by Simhopp. I am using the Gopro Frame by MatteoMeraldi instead of the one that comes with the Gopro so that I can keep the power connected to the Gopro for a long time lapse.

This is my first design using Fusion 360 so it took me some time to figure out everything!

5-9-2017
I had to upload an updated version with the horizontal plate a little longer to avoid the bed from getting to close when doing the 9 point autolevel. Now if 10 mm further which avoids this base touching the bed.

Link to youtube video with some time-lapse samples using this mount.. https://youtu.be/a8GB1K12h_Y

description.text: This is designed to be a custom mount for a pair of Bose QC-15 headphones to be mounted on the front panel of my NZXT S340 case. It uses 2 rare earth magnets 1/2" in diameter and 1/8" thick.

READ ME

So my makerbot replicator mini + warped the bottom, which happened to be the side that the magnets would interact with - I had to sand it down with 60 grit sandpaper.

The supporting bean had edges that were too thin for the makerbot to print properly, resulting in this feather-textured edge. It looks okay though.

The raft failed to detach properly, hence the saw.

In the end, I feel the layer between the magnets and the edge of the piece was too far; I needed about an inch of masking tape to finally make it stick properly in addition to the magnets. I would reduce this to the bare minimum (editing pending)

Tolerances were much better than I thought, I made the holes slightly bigger for the magnets but I probably didn't have to.

I would recommend adding more magnets.

Meet the AX-03 Railgun 3D Printer.

The ethos of this 3D Printer is to keep costs down, but be as rigid as possible with smooth movement, along with having a light weight direct drive extruder. This is why it uses 2040 Extrusion for the main frame. MGN Linear rails for the motion and the Drakon Geared Extruder in direct drive configuration.

It is essentially a souped up Direct Drive Prusa i3 Style printer with none of the drawbacks of a standard i3. EG, only 1 Z motor is used with reciprocal belted motion to the 2nd lead screw to keep it all in sync.

Files here are not always up to date, please use the Github at https://github.com/AxMod3DPrint/AX-03-Railgun for the latest file versions

description.text: Based on a pencil sharpener! It creates a rounded shaft, useful for making Arrows and dowels . There are adjustment screws for the 32mm chisel (needed) so you can make bigger or smaller arrows. See Video of it in action here http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tL0jMKL5U5Q Not sure how many arrows this will cut before the plastic wares away with friction. Thinking about it afterwards the captive nuts could have been better placed and a little less tight, anybody want to improve on this design please do. The small output tube is the diameter of the cut arrow. The larger hole is tapered towards the output tube. The blade must be position at the top height of the output tube so when the wood reaches the tube it should already be cut to fit. The dogleg is for placing into a vice or screwing to the side of a workbench

Print in ABS with three shells and 50% infill (this needs to be a workhorse) have not tried PLA and sure it would not work well due to friction heat. You will need 2 50mm m4 bolts and 3 16mm m4 bolts that are used for adjusting the blade position. You may need to cut the 50s down if your chisel isn't very fat. Clamp the chisel down using the bolts, position the blade so that about 1mm is over the tapered ledge. Clamp it or screw to the side of a workbench using the provided holes on the dogleg. Cut your stock wood down to 12mm or 10mm square and trim off both the ends by hand using the Arrow Thingy so that you have a nice starting angle when using the drill Attach one end of the wood stock to a hand drill and keeping the wood in the center run the drill fast,and push through the hole. Your first run will burn off some plastic, don't worry it's just finding itself :) Make sure you keep the stock in the center of the large tapered input hole as you push the wood through.

title: Anycubic i3 Dual Z Endstop Fix

description.text:
So I found my Anycubic i3 Dual not reliably homing because the Z endstop was sliding along the holes it's designed to be fastened to. So I had 2 options: Tighten the screws even more or print a suitable mount. In the instructions they even told me to not fasten the screws too tight because the microswitch may break. Thats why I went with the latter option and made a part that the switch sits in and which can be screwed down pretty tight (until the acrylic frame breaks).
As an added bonus theres a small channel for the X motor's wire.

Note before printing that I mounted the adjustment screw the wrong way around, resulting this mount being too high for a correctly inserted screw. I'm just too lazy to flip the screw around.
Edit: Fixed the screw's orientation, it works either way.

This is a simple connector to join two 2-liter bottles together to make a Tornado Tube experiment for your kids. 
Fill one of the 2-liter bottles with water, connect, swirl, watch the tornado!

Steve Spangler Science sells these on his website: http://www.stevespanglerscience.com/product/1226 After making one for my sons instead, I decided that others needed this as well. :) You can see it in action here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dv6vQU94wws&feature=player_embedded It is the simple colored connector that you see Steve screw onto the 2-liter bottles.

Required items:
  • Two 2-liter bottles
  • Two 7/8" garden hose o-rings (hardware store)
  • One print of this Thing
    • While the o-rings aren't "required," I like to use them as it makes for a more water-tight seal. Instructions:
  • Print using 2-3 shells for water tightness.
  • Cut support material out of the center hole of the printed part.
  • Insert a 7/8" garden hose o-ring on both threaded sides.
  • Fill one of the two 2-liters 3/4 full of water.
  • Screw this Thing onto the full 2-liter and screw a second 2-liter to the other end.
  • Invert and swirl.
  • Watch the tornado!
    • Model notes: If you use the SCAD file to make alterations to this model, it also requires the "2LscrewPositive.11.stl" file from the "2 Liter bottle threads" thing found at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10489. Enjoy! Postscript: After publishing this, I found parkolay's "20_Oz_Bottle Adapter" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6090 that performs the same function. While they are very similar, mine will allow others to edit it via OpenSCAD. Also mine has a reducer in the center to make the tornado last longer while parkolay's does not.

description.text:
I designed this to be a template for cutting a 1/8th inch (3mm) aluminum sheet. It could be printed as well.

In this version i have utilized a lower duct under the gantry so you'll need to lower the extruders. This is why the sensor mount is printed separately.

I wanted access to the set screw for the heat breaks, so i turned the extruder around, and also designed a blower duct because I was not happy with the tiny 30mm fan's cooling.

The lower duct only needs bed supports because I designed it to be printed without. I believe I used .2mm layer height.

Print the Front duct with the extruder face down, using bed supports as well, I have included a version with built in supports if needed for the mounting slot, otherwise this was also designed to not need additional supports.

I have designed the duct supports to include an air filter. I just use an air conditioning filter and cut it to size, but you might be able to use something like a coffee filter, The benefit here is it should aid in filtering your print fumes and protect your fans from getting dirty. If you don't want the filter then you'll need to shim the lower part as its spaced for accommodation of the filter.

I choose to use flared copper pipe instead of the plastic tubing so that I can. use high temperature firmament without problem. Also the flared end made loading filament much easier, given that there is not much space between the extruders. However, its not required because you can still use the pfte tube to direct the filiment to the hot end.

This project has been a long time coming and is remixed from my original versions.

title: Meeseeks Box - Google AIY Voice for the Pi Zero W

description.text:
If you haven't printed yet, redownload the files as I've made a few minor tweaks for a better fit and alignment. I also realized the top of the box doesn't have a octogan in the middle, so I have created an Accurate Top as well as an Octo Top in case you like how it looks. The square supports underneath the microphone holes should be able to be popped off from the top, maybe poke a small screw driver threw to top holes.

This is designed to fit the Pi Zero W and will not fit larger Pi. Due to how tight the design is inside, I moved the microphone to the back of the box but everything still works fine. The hole in the back panel for the power supply is 5mm wide in case you need to widen it a little for your own power supply.

The Pi Zero W Holder is optional, as the Pi zero will sit nicely inside the hole on the bottom. I updated it to adjust some clearances. There's now a hole underneath to help with removal of the Pi. I also added a version that has Tree Supports generated in MeshMixer.

Video of it running:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vgi76dW5N3g

Assembly Video
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7mb9ln7fUww

  1. Install the button to the top panel. Insert the lamp so that the plugs and wires jut out to the left when looking at the box from behind. Clearance is VERY tight in this design, so you want everything facing properly.
  2. Install the Microphone PCB into the opening and tape it in place. Connect the plug.
  3. WITH THE MICROSD CARD REMOVED Place the Pi Zero W + Voice Hat into the Pi Zero W Holder. Once its in place, insert the microSD card.
  4. Connect your speaker wires to the the board. Plug in the Button cable as well as the Microphone cable.
  5. Now is a good time to plug in the power supply (the Mini USB end) . Place the Pi Zero W Holder into the opening inside the box. It should fit nicely in place to keep from moving around too much.
  6. Gently slide the top panel into the top slots and push it forward all the way. Move wires as necessary.
  7. Insert the back panel and guide it over the power supply cable.
  8. Knock yourselves out just keep your requests simple.

description.text:
Are all of your work surfaces level? Sadly, mine aren't (old house syndrome). Does your Makerbot Replicator 2/2X balance on three sides? Is your manual stuffed under one side to keep it from rocking?
Is so, it's time to put a stop to all that silliness!
While it may not matter (much) whether your Makerbot Rep2 is level, it certainly looks better when it is level! And not rocking has got to be a good thing.
I made this adjustable foot by using some left over 8mm adjusters from an Ikea bookshelf. I've included a .stl file of a foot that will accept an 8mm bolt if you don't have any extra Ikea bookshelf parts laying around. Just take an 8mm x 40mm or longer bolt, heat the end up and press it into the foot.
This work is a mashup of my part and the replacement feet from thing http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:219127.
If you want to use a different sized bolt, see the .scad file for directions on how to modify the part. Update 2014-07-27 : I added a new .scad file that imports the source object and positions it correctly for printing. Easier to use!

Print out (4) of the adjustable feet bases and (4) of the feet. Requires:
(4) 8mm x 40mm or longer bolts
(4) 8mm nuts
-or-
(4) 8mm adjusters from an Ikea bookshelf or similar
If you have to make the feet:
-- Heat the head of the 8mm bolt and press into the foot (or glue it in place).
-- Insert the nuts into the nut traps.
-- Thread the bolts into the adjusters,
else:
-- Thread the foot into each adjuster.
finally:
-- Replace all four of the original feet.
-- Adjust until unit is level.

remixed_from.title: Daily Equation #2 - Astroid x^(2/3) + y^(2/3) = a

description.text:
This is Day 7 of my collection of printable equations. To see the whole collection, go to: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:227210 For today's equation, I'm continuing the series of equations of the form |x^b + y^c| = a (See days 2 and 6). Previously, we saw that b = c = 1 generated a diamond, while b = c = 2/3 caused the diamond edges to curve inward. Today we look at b = c = 5/3, which bends the curve outward to start approaching a circle. Details:
  • units are in mm
  • a = 678 (to give a length and height of 100)
  • Range(x) = -50 to 50
  • stl resized to make x axis = 100 mm
    • As always, I'm going to continue to post one equation per day until get bored or people lose interest. If there's a particular equation you'd like to see, leave a comment and I'll give it a shot.
All files can be printed without support. Photos shown were printed on a Replicator 2 and sliced using the standard setting on Makerware.

I managed to design this drone propeller by using the Drela AG11 airfoil. Testing was performed on the Drone Propeller Thrust Tester (test results below).

Here are the readings for a few voltage presets (also visible in the pictures taken):

  • 1.5V => 13.19 grams
  • 2V => 21.87 grams
  • 2.5V => 30.34 grams
  • 3V => 36.28 grams

The included files consist of all shots taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the printable STL files and the SLDPRT files. Should you like to use the propeller, you should grab a bunch of 8520 coreless motors.

You should use the SLDPRT files, should you want to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

P.S. Airfoil plotted with the matplotlib library for python.

Finally, after almost a year, I had to disassemble my ToM's HBP to fix the infamous melted power pin. After putting it all back together my platform was wickedly out of level. 
Luckily for me, some time ago I had downloaded FAMULUS's "HBP Quick Leveler Redux" wheel 9-up plate and modified it to not have the large number of curves, rounded edges, and notches of the original. I just wanted something simple that RepG would slice in a few minutes, not the 20 or so minutes FAMULUS's plate was taking.
Because I was lazy, I used FAMULUS's STL for the screw and nut hole, and just built a new surrounding bit. I put a 9-up plate together and it sliced in around 3 minutes; estimated print time 19 minutes. This I could deal with :-)
This really is a great thing and any version should be part of every ToM owner's machine.

Print the plate using ABS, use two wheels on each corner bolt/nut as documented in FAMULUS's thing, leaving the two middle bolts wheel/nut-less. See: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13778 Added 8-up (since that's how many you need ;-) ) and a single STL.

After printing i rework my parts using a drill bit to clean the holes,and a sharp blade to clean the sides/cutouts of the printed part.
